In[127]:
# Impute missing values with median grouped by Sport and Sex in age, weight, and height
# Replacing NaN with "No Medal"in Medal column

df_cleaned.loc[:, "Age"] = df_cleaned.groupby(["Sport", "Sex"])["Age"].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Weight"] = df_cleaned.groupby(["Sport", "Sex"])["Weight"].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Height"] = df_cleaned.groupby(["Sport", "Sex"])["Height"].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Medal"] = df_cleaned["Medal"].fillna("No Medal")
print("\nNull Counts After Imputation:")
print(df_cleaned[["Age", "Weight", "Height", "Medal"]].isnull().sum())

Null Counts After Imputation:

Height    100
Medal       0

In[98]:
# Type conversion
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Year"] = df_cleaned["Year"].astype("category")
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Season"] = df_cleaned["Season"].astype("category")
In[128]:
# Creating BMI column based on BMI formula of Weight (kg) / [Height (m)]^2
df_cleaned.loc[:, "BMI"] = df_cleaned["Weight"] / ((df_cleaned["Height"] / 100) ** 2)
In[129]:
# Creating Age Group Column
bins = [0, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 100]
labels = ["<15", "16-20", "21-25", "26-30", "31-35", "35+"]
df_cleaned.loc[:, "Age_Group"] = pd.cut(df_cleaned["Age"], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=True)
print("\n--- Final Cleaned Data Info (with new features) ---")
df_cleaned.info()

In[142]:
# Gender Participation Over Time
# Using groupby to group by year and sex, as well as count the number of participants + turn new results into a new dataframe
df_gender = df_cleaned.groupby(['Year', 'Sex'])['ID'].count().reset_index()
df_gender.rename(columns={'ID': 'Participants'}, inplace=True)

sns.lineplot(data=df_gender,
    x="Year",
    y="Participants",
    hue="Sex",        
    linewidth=2
)
plt.title("Gender Participation Over 120 Years of Olympics")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of Participants")
plt.show()

# Interpretation:
# Historically, men have dominated regarding participation; male participants continue to constantly outnumber the total amount of women participants.
# A greater push for equality (probably coupled with Title IX in America) supports the steay increade of women participation from the 60s and onward.
# The gender gap in the Olympics seems to be closing (based off the trends of the last 20 or so years).
# The Olympics have gotten more globalized and inclusive in modern history, as the total amount participants has significant increased as of the 2010s.

# Interpretation:

# The age distribution for Gold medalists is more compact than the other medal types
# There are outliers that are very young and old across all medal types; this shows the speciailization of Olympic sports as the younger ones come from events like Swimming and Gymnastics, while the older ones come from more procesion oriented events like sailing and shooting.

# The majority of olympic participants cluster around the average body type, which reflects the necessity of athleticism in the Olympics

# Medal Count by Sport
# First, need to group sport and medal and count the occurrences. Then, unstack the medals
# After, calculate the total amount of medals per sport, find the top 10 sports, and drop the total column

sport_medal_counts = df_medals.groupby(["Sport", "Medal"])["ID"].count().unstack(fill_value=0)
sport_medal_counts["Total"] = sport_medal_counts.sum(axis=1)
top_ten_sports_medals = sport_medal_counts.sort_values(by="Total", ascending=False).head(10).drop("Total", axis=1)
top_ten_sports_medals = top_ten_sports_medals.sort_values(by="Gold", ascending=True)

# The top events by medal wins (Atletics, Swimming, Gymnastics) offer more individual events than the other 7 entries; a single country or athlete could win multiple medals in the same discipline.
# The distribution of each medal type (about 1/3 for each) is consist across the top sports; no sport disproportionately awards one medal type over another.
# Does not necessarily reflect the global popularity or difficulty/competitiveness of all the events

# Medal Distribution (Pie Chart)
# First, need to filter out actual medalists
# Then count the frequency of gold, silver, and bronze medals
df_medals = df_cleaned[df_cleaned["Medal"] != "No Medal"].copy()
medal_counts = df_medals["Medal"].value_counts().reindex(["Gold", "Silver", "Bronze"])

plt.pie(
    medal_counts,
    labels=medal_counts.index,      # Labels for the slices (Gold, Silver, Bronze)
    autopct='%1.1f%%',              # Displays the percentage on each slice
    startangle=90,                  # Start the first slice from the top (12 o'clock)
    colors=["gold", "silver", "peru"], # Define custom colors for medal types
    wedgeprops={"edgecolor": "black"}  # Add black outline to slices
)
plt.title("Distribution of Gold, Silver, and Bronze Medals")
plt.show()

# Interpretation:
# There are no anomalies (i.e., one medal type taking up 50% of the distribution).
# There's nearly perfect proportionality, which shows the structural integrity of the dataset; data has been accurately and fairly recorded.
In[148]:
# Heatmap
# First, select key variables (columns) then calculate correlation matrix, which is needed to show the strength and direction between the variables
corr_cols = ["Age", "Height", "Weight", "BMI", "Year"]
df_corr = df_cleaned[corr_cols].corr() # .corr() shows the matrix

fig = px.imshow(
    df_corr,
    text_auto=True,                      # Displaying correlation values on the heatmap
    aspect="auto",
    color_continuous_scale=px.colors.sequential.Inferno, # Choosing a color scale
    x=df_corr.columns, # Labeling the axes using the correlation matrix index/columns
    y=df_corr.index
)

fig.update_layout(
    title="Correlation Heatmap of Athlete Attributes and Year",
    xaxis_title="Attribute",
    yaxis_title="Attribute",
    xaxis={"side": "bottom"}
)

fig.show()

# Interpretation:
# There's an interdependence of the physical attributes (weight, height, BMI), as indicated by the strong positive correlations between weight and BMI, as well as height and weight.
# The average or target body type has been consistent throughout 120 years of olympic history, as highlighted by the negative correlation of year and physical attributes
# Body type (BMI) is separate from age; the desired/required size is determined by the specifc sport not one's age--this is seen  by all correlation coefficients involving age being near 0.

# General trends in Olympic history and participation:

participation_over_time = df_cleaned.groupby("Year")["ID"].count()

gender_participation_time = df_cleaned.groupby(["Year", "Sex"])["ID"].count().unstack(fill_value=0)

# Total participation from the first games in 1896 to the most recent in 2016 has significantly increased; this can be explained by the globalization of the games as well as inclusion of women.
# There's structural bias toward high-volume events in the total medal count; medal count doesn't exactly correlate with competitiveness and difficulty of respective sports and events (as seen in the bar plot).
# The correlation heatmap shows that the average athlete has not gotten older, taller, or heavier over the 120 years of Olympic history.

# Do host countries tend to win more medals?
# First, I define host country mapping (a dictionary) and identify host rows by creating a new column (Host_Identifier)
# In creating the new column, I utilize the zip() method to combine the year and city columns into tuple pairs to make the new column's values match the keys in the host mapping dictionary.
# Then, I create and filter a new dataframe. After that, calculate the overall average of medals per year, the host year medals and then merge and compare the values.

host_mapping = {
    (2016, "Rio de Janeiro"): "Brazil", (2012, "London"): "Great Britain",
    (2008, "Beijing"): "China", (2004, "Athina"): "Greece",
    (2000, "Sydney"): "Australia", (1996, "Atlanta"): "USA"
}
df_medals["Host_Identifier"] = list(zip(df_medals["Year"], df_medals["City"]))
df_host_events = df_medals[df_medals.apply(
    lambda row: row["region"] == host_mapping.get(row["Host_Identifier"], None), 
    axis=1
)].copy()

avg_medals_per_year = df_medals.groupby("region")["Year"].agg(["count", "nunique"]).reset_index()
avg_medals_per_year["Overall_Avg_Medals"] = avg_medals_per_year["count"] / avg_medals_per_year["nunique"]
avg_medals_per_year = avg_medals_per_year.rename(columns={"region": "Country"})
host_year_medals = df_host_events.groupby("region")["Medal"].count().reset_index().rename(columns={"Medal": "Host_Medals", "region": "Country"})
df_comparison = host_year_medals.merge(
    avg_medals_per_year[["Country", "Overall_Avg_Medals"]], 
    on="Country"
)

df_plot = df_comparison.melt(
    id_vars="Country", 
    value_vars=["Host_Medals", "Overall_Avg_Medals"],
    var_name="Type", 
    value_name="Medals"
) # Converting the dataframe to long format for easier plotting

# Accompanying bar graph
sns.barplot(
    data=df_plot,
    x="Country",
    y="Medals",
    hue="Type",
    palette={"Host_Medals": "skyblue", "Overall_Avg_Medals": "grey"}
)
plt.title("Medal Count in Host Year vs. Overall Average Performance")
plt.xlabel("Host Country")
plt.ylabel("Total Medals Won")
plt.legend(title="Performance Metric", labels=["Host Year Medals", "Overall Average Medals"])
plt.show()

# Yes; host countries usually have significantly more medal wins compared to their average medal performance.
